insert into public.questions
  (id, parent_id, type, category, subtopic, importance, difficulty, candidate_level, region, question, key_points, model_answer)
values
(1836, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Technology DD$x$, 'core', 3, 'intern', 'Global', $x$Walk me through what you would actually look at in an IT or technology due diligence on a software or tech-enabled target, and what the deliverable to the deal team looks like.$x$, $x$["Tech stack review - languages, frameworks, cloud, end-of-life components", "Scalability - can architecture handle 2-3x load without a rewrite", "Technical debt - shortcuts, undocumented code, single points of failure", "Key-engineer / bus-factor dependence on the core system", "Security and data practices, especially for AI/data-enabled targets", "Integration / migration risk to acquirer systems post-close", "Output = remediation costs and timelines fed into model and value-creation plan"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Technology due diligence asks whether the target's technology can actually support the business plan we are paying for. I start with the tech stack - what languages, frameworks, databases and cloud infrastructure they run, and whether any of it is end-of-life or unsupported. Then scalability: can the architecture handle two or three times the load without a rewrite, or is it stitched together in a way that breaks under growth. I look hard at technical debt - shortcuts, undocumented code, single points of failure, over-reliance on one engineer who wrote the core system. Security and data practices matter too, especially for anything AI or data-enabled. And I assess integration risk - how painful it will be to connect or migrate their systems to ours post-close. The output is not a yes or no; it is a list of remediation costs and timelines the deal team can fold into the model and the value creation plan.$x$),
(1837, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Legal DD Scope$x$, 'core', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$What does legal due diligence cover, and how do its findings flow into the deal documents?$x$, $x$["Corporate - clean cap table, properly issued shares, control", "Material contracts - customer/supplier, change-of-control clauses", "Litigation - pending or threatened, pattern of disputes", "IP ownership - core IP genuinely owned, contractor assignments", "Regulatory/compliance, employment, real estate matters", "Findings feed reps and warranties and disclosure schedules", "Can drive a price chip or a specific indemnity"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Legal due diligence is the workstream that checks whether the target actually owns what we think it owns and whether anything in its contracts or history could blow up the deal. I would scope it across a few buckets. First, corporate - is the cap table clean, are the shares properly issued, who really controls the company. Second, material contracts - the big customer and supplier agreements, looking especially for change-of-control clauses that let a counterparty walk or reprice if ownership changes. Third, litigation - pending or threatened lawsuits, and any pattern of disputes. Fourth, intellectual property - does the company genuinely own its core IP, or was key code written by contractors who never assigned rights. Fifth, regulatory and compliance, plus employment and real estate matters. The findings feed the reps and warranties, the disclosure schedules, and sometimes a price chip or a specific indemnity.$x$),
(1838, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Tax DD And Structuring$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'US', $x$How does tax due diligence work, and how do tax findings interact with how we structure the acquisition - for example asset versus stock deal?$x$, $x$["Two jobs - historical exposures plus deal structuring", "Exposures - unpaid tax, transfer pricing, sales/VAT, payroll, open audits", "Covered by reps / indemnity / escrow / tax insurance", "Asset deal gives buyer stepped-up basis and D&A shield", "Seller often resists asset deal - recapture and double tax raise seller tax", "Test NOL value and Section 382 change-of-ownership limits", "Directly affects after-tax cash flow and price"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Tax due diligence has two jobs - find historical exposures and shape how we structure the acquisition. On the exposure side I look for unpaid or underpaid taxes, aggressive positions that could be challenged, transfer pricing issues in multinationals, sales and use or VAT errors, payroll and worker-classification risk, and any open audits. These are contingent liabilities that get covered by reps, indemnities, escrow, or increasingly tax insurance. On structuring, the big question is asset versus stock deal. An asset deal usually gives the buyer a stepped-up basis and future depreciation and amortization shields, which has real cash value, but the seller often resists because recapture and double tax on a C-corp can mean higher tax to them. I would also test the value of net operating losses and whether a change of ownership limits their use under Section 382. The point is that tax is not just a risk scan - it directly affects after-tax cash flow and therefore what we can pay.$x$),
(1839, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Environmental DD$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$When and how would you run environmental due diligence, and what do Phase I and Phase II assessments give you?$x$, $x$["Matters for industrial/energy/property-owning targets", "Liabilities long-tailed; in some regimes attach to owner regardless of fault", "Phase I = records and site review for evidence of contamination", "Phase II = actual soil/groundwater sampling if Phase I flags something", "Permits, compliance history, notices of violation", "Outputs - cleanup cost, compliance capex, insurance, indemnity", "Can move price or kill the deal on a contaminated site"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Environmental due diligence matters most for industrial, manufacturing, energy, or anything that owns or operates real property, because environmental liabilities can be large, long-tailed, and in some regimes attach to the owner regardless of fault. The standard starting point is a Phase I environmental site assessment - a records and site review looking for evidence of contamination or prior risky uses. If that flags something, a Phase II involves actual sampling of soil and groundwater. I am also looking at permits and whether the target is operating within them, compliance history and notices of violation, hazardous materials handling, and emerging exposures like remediation obligations or asbestos. The findings can translate into estimated cleanup costs, ongoing compliance capex, environmental insurance, or specific indemnities from the seller. On a big contaminated site this can move the price or, occasionally, kill the deal entirely.$x$),
(1840, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Insurance DD$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$What are you trying to learn in insurance due diligence, and why can underinsurance be a debt-like item?$x$, $x$["Map existing program - GL, property, D&O, product, cyber, WC", "Check limits, deductibles, exclusions, change-of-control lapse", "Loss-run history - claims running hot vs premiums", "Coverage gaps - uninsured/self-insured tails", "Underinsurance = future funding need = debt-like", "Post-close D&O tail policy for the prior board", "Feeds the cost model and the IC risk picture"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Insurance due diligence checks whether the target is adequately covered today and what coverage will really cost us going forward. I start by mapping the existing program - general liability, property, directors and officers, product liability, cyber, workers comp - and checking limits, deductibles, exclusions, and whether any policies lapse or terminate on a change of control. Then I pull the loss-run history, which is the record of past claims, to see if losses are running hot relative to premiums; that often signals an operational problem and predicts future premium increases. I look for gaps - uninsured or self-insured exposures, especially product or environmental tails. Underinsurance is a debt-like item in disguise because we will have to fund it. Post-close, some coverage like D and O usually needs a tail policy for the prior board. The output feeds both the cost model and the risk picture for the investment committee.$x$),
(1841, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Lease And Property DD$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$For a target with a large leased real-estate footprint, like retail or distribution, what would your real-estate and lease due diligence focus on?$x$, $x$["Build a lease abstract per site - term, renewals, escalators", "Repair/tax responsibility under lease (net vs gross)", "Change-of-control / assignment clauses trigger consent or termination", "Above-market rents overstate margins", "Near-term expiries on critical sites = renewal risk", "Long-dated operating leases sit close to debt", "Output - normalized occupancy cost and expiry schedule"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Real estate and lease diligence asks what the target's property footprint really costs and how locked-in it is. For a leased portfolio - think retail or distribution - I build a lease abstract for every site: remaining term, renewal options, rent escalators, who pays for repairs and taxes under the lease, and any change-of-control or assignment clauses that could trigger consent or termination on the deal. I am looking for above-market rents that overstate margins, near-term expiries on critical sites that create renewal risk, and onerous leases we would want to exit but cannot cheaply. Long-dated operating leases are also a real claim on cash and sit close to debt in how I think about them. For owned property I check title, valuations, and any environmental or zoning issues. The output is a normalized occupancy cost, a schedule of expiry and renewal risk, and any leases that need to be restructured or terminated.$x$),
(1842, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Workforce And Labor DD$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$Beyond key-person risk, how do you diligence the broader workforce - compensation, retention, change-of-control payouts, and labor relations - and how does it hit the deal?$x$, $x$["Comp benchmarking - at/above/below market, wage-inflation risk", "Retention and regrettable attrition in engineering/sales", "Single-trigger acceleration / golden parachutes pay on deal", "Option pool refresh to retain talent", "Labor relations - unions, CBAs, expiry, strike history", "Unfunded items - accrued vacation, deferred comp, wage-and-hour claims", "Either hits the model as cost or shapes the retention plan"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Beyond key-person risk, people diligence is really about the cost, stickiness, and risk embedded in the workforce. On compensation, I check whether the target is paying at, above, or below market - underpayment means we will face wage inflation post-close, and rich pay means a margin problem. I look at retention and attrition data, especially regrettable attrition in engineering or sales. Change-of-control and equity matters are big: do executives have single-trigger acceleration or golden parachutes that pay out on the deal, and will the option pool need refreshing to keep people. Then labor relations - any unions, collective bargaining agreements, their expiry dates, and the history of disputes or strikes. I also scan for unfunded liabilities like accrued vacation, deferred comp, or pending employment litigation and wage-and-hour claims. All of it either hits the model as cost or shapes the retention plan we need to land the talent.$x$),
(1843, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Pension And Contingent Liabilities$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$How do you treat defined-benefit pensions, OPEB, and other contingent liabilities in a deal, and how do they flow into the bridge from enterprise to equity value?$x$, $x$["Funded status = plan assets minus the benefit obligation (PBO/DBO)", "Underfunding treated as debt-like, often net of tax", "Regulatory funding shortfall can differ from the accounting number", "Stress the discount rate - a high rate flatters the liability", "OPEB usually unfunded, large for legacy industrials", "Other contingents - litigation, warranty, remediation, earn-outs", "Decide net-debt deduction vs indemnity/insurance cover"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Defined-benefit pensions and other post-employment benefits like retiree healthcare are classic debt-like items because they are real obligations the buyer inherits. The key number is the funded status - plan assets minus the benefit obligation, the PBO under US GAAP or the DBO under IFRS. If the plan is underfunded by, say, fifty million, I would generally treat that shortfall, often on a more conservative regulatory funding basis and net of tax, as a deduction from equity value alongside debt, because we will have to top it up over time. I stress the discount rate the actuaries used - a high rate flatters the liability, so a small change can swing the number materially. OPEB is usually unfunded entirely and can be large for legacy industrials. Beyond pensions, contingent liabilities include litigation reserves, warranty obligations, environmental remediation, and earn-outs from the target's own past deals. I probe whether reserves are adequate and decide what to reflect in net debt versus cover with indemnities or insurance.$x$),
(1844, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Cohort Retention Curves$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A SaaS target shows you monthly revenue cohort curves. The early-month cohorts flatten out around 80% retained, but the most recent cohorts are decaying faster in their first few months. How do you read this, and what would you do to figure out whether it is a real problem?$x$, $x$["Cohort = group acquired in same period tracked over time", "Flattening tail signals a stable, sticky core", "Faster early decay in new cohorts = deteriorating quality or onboarding", "Separate logo churn from dollar churn and net expansion", "Check if newer cohorts came from new channel, segment, or discount", "Watch survivorship - newer cohorts have less aging", "Pull driver-level data before concluding churn is structural"]$x$::jsonb, $x$So a cohort curve tracks each group of customers from the month they were acquired and shows how much of that starting revenue survives over time. Older cohorts flattening near 80 percent is actually encouraging, because it points to a sticky core that stops churning once it is past the early danger zone. What worries me is newer cohorts decaying faster in their first few months, since that hints the quality of recent acquisition is slipping. So I would first split this into logo churn versus dollar churn and look at net revenue retention separately, because downgrades and expansion move differently. Then I would ask what changed about how the new cohorts were sourced, since a new channel, a cheaper price point, a different segment, or a promotion can all pull in worse-fitting customers. I would also watch for survivorship, because the youngest cohorts simply have not aged yet, so I would compare every cohort at the same number of months since acquisition. Only after pulling the driver-level data would I judge whether this is structural or a temporary mix shift.$x$),
(1845, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Unit Economics Validation$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A consumer subscription target tells you their LTV-to-CAC is 4 to 1 and CAC payback is eight months. Walk me through how you would pressure-test those two numbers before you trust them in the model.$x$, $x$["Rebuild LTV from gross margin and retention curve, not revenue", "Check discount rate and capped lifetime assumption", "CAC must be fully loaded - all S&M, not just paid media", "Blended vs paid CAC can hide organic dependence", "Payback on contribution margin, not revenue", "Cohort-level payback vs blended average", "Stress churn and margin to see how fast ratio breaks"]$x$::jsonb, $x$My instinct is that both numbers are only as good as their inputs, so I would rebuild them from scratch. For LTV, I want it built on gross margin rather than revenue, using the actual retention curve instead of one over a churn rate, and I would check whether they capped the lifetime and discounted future cash flows, because an uncapped LTV on a long-tail curve can look enormous. For CAC, the classic trap is that it has to be fully loaded, meaning all sales and marketing spend including salaries and tooling, not just paid media. I would also separate blended CAC from paid CAC, because if a lot of growth is organic the paid CAC is much worse and harder to scale. On payback, I want it measured on contribution margin, not revenue, and ideally cohort by cohort rather than a blended average that mixes good and bad vintages. Then I would stress the churn and margin assumptions, because if a small move in retention swings the ratio from four to one down toward two to one, the unit economics are far more fragile than the headline suggests.$x$),
(1846, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Sales Pipeline DD$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$You are doing diligence on a B2B software company whose forecast leans heavily on a CRM pipeline they say is worth three times next year's new-bookings target. How do you assess whether that pipeline actually supports the plan?$x$, $x$["Weight pipeline by stage conversion, not gross value", "Build historical stage-to-close and win rates from CRM", "Test coverage ratio against historical close rates", "Check pipeline aging, push rates, and stuck deals", "Concentration in a few mega-deals or one rep", "Hygiene - duplicate, stale, or sandbagged opportunities", "Reconcile bookings to billings to revenue downstream"]$x$::jsonb, $x$A three-times coverage ratio sounds comfortable, but the gross pipeline number means very little on its own, so I would weight it by realistic conversion. I would pull several years of CRM history, build stage-by-stage conversion and overall win rates, then apply those to the current pipeline by stage to get a probability-weighted figure I can compare against the bookings target. I want to know whether three-times coverage has historically been enough, because if they normally close one in four and the plan needs one in three, the pipeline is actually thin. Then I would look at aging and push rates, since deals that keep slipping quarter to quarter are a warning sign, and I would check concentration, because if a few mega-deals or a single star rep carry the number the risk profile is very different. I would also test hygiene for duplicates, stale opportunities, and sandbagging. Finally I would trace the chain from bookings to billings to revenue, because a strong pipeline still has to convert into recognized revenue on the timeline the model assumes, and that is where optimistic plans tend to break.$x$),
(1847, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Supply Chain DD$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A mid-market industrial manufacturer sources a critical component from a single overseas supplier that accounts for roughly 40% of its cost of goods. How do you scope the supply-chain diligence, and how does this risk show up in the deal?$x$, $x$["Quantify single-source vs sole-source distinction", "Switching cost, qualification time, tooling ownership", "Contract terms - exclusivity, pricing, term, change-of-control", "Supplier financial health and concentration the other way", "Inventory buffers, lead times, geographic and tariff exposure", "Margin sensitivity to input-cost or FX moves", "Reflect in price, reps, or a specific risk mitigation plan"]$x$::jsonb, $x$The first thing I would establish is whether this is single-source by choice or sole-source because no one else can make the part, because that changes everything. So I would map the switching cost: how long qualifying an alternate supplier takes, who owns the tooling, and whether customer or regulatory approvals are involved. Then I would read the supply contract closely for exclusivity, pricing mechanics, remaining term, and crucially any change-of-control clause that lets the supplier walk or reprice on a deal. I would assess the supplier's own financial health and whether our target is a tiny customer to them, which weakens leverage. I would look at inventory buffers and lead times, plus geographic and tariff exposure, since with higher rates and trade friction this is exactly where margin and cash conversion get squeezed. I would also run margin sensitivity to input-cost and FX moves to see how much EBITDA is really at risk. In the deal this could show up as a price chip, a specific representation, or a post-close dual-sourcing plan we would underwrite explicitly.$x$),
(1848, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Capex Maintenance Vs Growth$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A target reports total capex of 8% of revenue but tells you most of it is growth capex, implying maintenance needs are low and free cash flow is strong. How do you test that split and the underlying asset condition?$x$, $x$["Maintenance capex = spend to sustain current capacity", "Growth capex expands capacity or new capability", "Companies overstate growth to flatter free cash flow", "Benchmark vs D&A and against peers", "Asset age, useful life, deferred maintenance backlog", "Site visits and technical advisor on plant condition", "Impact on normalized FCF and entry multiple"]$x$::jsonb, $x$This matters because management has every incentive to label spend as growth, since maintenance capex is a real claim on free cash flow while growth capex looks discretionary. So I would not take the split at face value. Maintenance capex is what is needed just to keep current capacity running, and growth capex expands capacity or adds new capability. One quick triangulation is to compare maintenance capex against depreciation, because if reported maintenance sits far below D&A for an asset-heavy business, that is a flag the assets are being run down. I would benchmark total and maintenance capex as a percent of revenue against peers, and look hard at asset age, remaining useful life, and any deferred maintenance backlog. For a manufacturing target I would push for site visits and a technical advisor to assess plant condition directly, since deferred maintenance is effectively hidden capex that hits the buyer later. Then I would rebuild normalized free cash flow on a realistic maintenance number, because if true maintenance is higher than claimed, the cash flow and the multiple I can pay both come down.$x$),
(1849, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Deferred Revenue And RPO$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$For a subscription software target, walk me through how you use deferred revenue, RPO, and the bookings-to-billings relationship together to judge the durability of the revenue base in diligence.$x$, $x$["Deferred revenue = billed not yet recognized, a liability", "RPO captures contracted revenue including unbilled backlog", "Billings = revenue plus change in deferred revenue", "Bookings-to-billings shows new demand vs amounts invoiced", "Watch annual vs monthly billing skewing deferred", "Current vs long-term RPO for near-term visibility", "Deferred revenue haircut as a debt-like / purchase-accounting item"]$x$::jsonb, $x$I think of these three as different vantage points on the same contracted revenue. Deferred revenue is cash the company has billed but not yet earned, so it sits as a liability and tells me what is already locked in for the near term. RPO is broader because it captures total contracted revenue including amounts not yet billed, so it shows the full backlog, and I would split current RPO from long-term to gauge the next twelve months specifically. Billings, which I back into as revenue plus the change in deferred revenue, tells me what the company actually invoiced, and comparing bookings to billings shows whether new demand is keeping pace with what is being billed. A wrinkle I always check is billing frequency, because a shift from annual to monthly invoicing shrinks deferred revenue without any real deterioration, so I would not misread that. I would also flag that in a deal the deferred revenue is often written down under purchase accounting and can carry a real cash cost to deliver against, so it sometimes gets treated as a debt-like item in the bridge.$x$),
(1850, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Negative Working Capital Risk$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$A fast-growing subscription business runs structurally negative working capital - customers prepay and it pays suppliers in arrears. Management points to this as a free funding source. In diligence, how do you assess that claim and what risk does it create for the deal?$x$, $x$["Negative NWC means customers/suppliers fund operations", "Confirm it is structural, not stretched payables or pulled-forward deferral", "Decompose into DSO, DIO, DPO and trend over time", "Key risk: the cash tailwind reverses when growth slows", "Separate deferred revenue (contract liability) from trade NWC", "Set peg off a normalized run-rate reflecting the model", "Slowdown hits earnings and the cash unwind simultaneously"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Negative working capital here is a feature, not a red flag: subscribers prepay and the company pays suppliers later, so customers effectively fund operations and growth releases cash rather than consuming it. In diligence my first job is to confirm it is structural and durable, not a one-off from stretching payables or pulling deferred revenue forward right before the data cut. So I would decompose it into DSO, DIO, and DPO and trend each over a couple of years to see what is really driving the negative balance and whether it is stable. The key risk is that this dynamic reverses if growth slows: a business that releases cash while scaling will consume cash as it decelerates, so the working-capital tailwind in the plan can quietly become a headwind. I would also separate the deferred-revenue piece, since that is contract liability rather than classic trade working capital and behaves differently. For the deal I would set the peg off a normalized run-rate that reflects this model, and I would flag that a sudden growth slowdown hits both earnings and the cash unwind at the same time.$x$),
(1851, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Data Room Setup$x$, 'core', 2, 'intern', 'Global', $x$You are staffed on a buy-side deal and the target has just opened a virtual data room. Walk me through how a buy-side team actually works through a VDR and the information-request process in the first couple of weeks.$x$, $x$["VDR Structure By Workstream Folders", "Index Review And Gap Log", "Tracker For Outstanding Requests", "Submit Questions Through Q And A Function", "Route Items To Right Workstream Lead", "Watch Staged Or Tiered Disclosure", "Flag Missing Or Stale Documents Early"]$x$::jsonb, $x$When a data room opens, the first thing I do is pull the index and map every folder to our workstreams - financial, legal, commercial, tax, HR - so I know what exists and, more importantly, what is missing. I build a request tracker: each open item gets an owner, a priority and a status, and I keep it live because partners and lawyers all pull from it. Questions go in through the room's structured Q and A function rather than email, so there is an audit trail and the seller's advisers can route answers. Early on I am triaging - is a document just not uploaded yet, genuinely unavailable, or being withheld - and I escalate gaps fast because they drive timing. I also watch for staged disclosure, where sensitive items like customer contracts or the model only come in later tranches, and for stale documents that predate the latest period. The goal in the first weeks is to turn a messy room into a clean gap log so the deal team can focus diligence where it actually matters.$x$),
(1852, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Confirmatory Versus Full$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$A client tells you they only want confirmatory diligence on this acquisition rather than full diligence. What does that distinction mean in practice, and when is confirmatory diligence appropriate versus dangerous?$x$, $x$["Full DD Tests Whole Thesis From Scratch", "Confirmatory Validates Specific Known Assumptions", "Driven By Prior Knowledge Or Vendor DD", "Narrower Scope Faster Timeline", "Appropriate When Buyer Already Knows Asset", "Risk Of Missing Unscoped Issues", "Scope Caveats In Reliance And Reports"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Full diligence tests the whole investment thesis from the ground up - you are validating the numbers, the market, the legal position and the risks without assuming much. Confirmatory diligence is narrower: the buyer already believes they understand the asset and just wants to confirm a defined set of assumptions before signing, so scope is tighter and the timeline is shorter. It is appropriate when the buyer is a trade player who knows the sector intimately, where there is robust vendor DD to rely on, or in a competitive auction where you simply cannot run a full process before bidding. The danger is scoping too tightly and missing something material that sat outside the confirmatory lens - a hidden liability, a churn problem, an integration blocker - because nobody was asked to look. I would be explicit about what is in and out of scope, document those caveats, and make sure reliance language in any third-party reports matches the reduced work actually done.$x$),
(1853, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Auction Versus Bilateral$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$How does the way you run diligence differ between a broad competitive auction and a proprietary bilateral deal? Think about sequencing, access and how you manage cost and risk.$x$, $x$["Auction Phased Access With Many Bidders", "Rely Heavily On Vendor DD And Limited Early Access", "Spend Gated To Avoid Sunk Cost On Lost Deals", "Bilateral Deeper Direct Management Access", "Sequence Confirmatory Work After Exclusivity", "Negotiate Reliance And Exclusivity Periods", "Private Credit Lenders Diligence In Parallel Fast"]$x$::jsonb, $x$In a broad auction you are one of many bidders, so access is rationed and phased - a teaser, then an IM and a populated data room, then management presentations, and full access often only after you are shortlisted. Early on you lean heavily on vendor DD and your own desktop work, and you deliberately gate spend, because committing serious third-party fees before you know you can win is how you burn money on deals you lose. You pace the heavy confirmatory work to land just before bids or in exclusivity. A proprietary bilateral deal is the opposite: you usually get deeper, earlier management access and can sequence diligence more rationally, but you carry more of the cost yourself because there is no shared vendor pack and no competitive tension to discipline the seller. In both, if private credit is funding you, those lenders run their own diligence in parallel and move quickly, so I coordinate work streams and reliance arrangements so the financing and the buyer are not duplicating effort or tripping over exclusivity windows.$x$),
(1854, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Vendor DD Preparation$x$, 'advanced', 4, 'associate', 'Global', $x$You are advising a seller and want to commission high-quality vendor due diligence ahead of a sale. How do you scope and prepare the vendor DD so it actually holds up with buyers and their lenders?$x$, $x$["Scope To Anticipate Buyer Concerns", "Independent Adviser With Genuine Duty Of Care", "Robust QoE And Databook Underpinning", "Address Not Hide Known Issues", "Fact Base Consistent With Management Model", "Reliance Addressed To Buyer And Lenders", "Timing So Reports Are Current At Signing"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Good vendor DD is written for the buyer, not the seller, so I start by anticipating exactly what an acquirer and their lenders will dig into - earnings quality, customer concentration, net debt and debt-like items, churn - and scope the reports to meet those questions head on. I appoint genuinely independent advisers whose reports can be addressed to and relied upon by buyers and financing parties, because reliance is what makes the pack worth anything in an auction. Underneath the reports I want a rock-solid QoE and a clean databook that ties to the management model, so the fact base is consistent everywhere a buyer looks. I do not hide known issues; I get ahead of them with a clear narrative and supporting analysis, because a problem the buyer finds themselves costs far more in price and trust than one you disclose well. I also manage timing so the reports are current at signing - stale vendor DD invites a buyer to reopen scope and rerun confirmatory work, which kills the speed advantage the seller paid for.$x$),
(1855, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$Day One Planning$x$, 'standard', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$As diligence wraps up on an acquisition, the deal team starts talking about Day-1 readiness and a 100-day plan. How should findings from DD feed integration planning, and what belongs on Day-1 versus the first 100 days?$x$, $x$["DD Findings Feed Integration Priorities", "Day One Continuity And Control Items", "TSAs For Separated Or Shared Functions", "100 Day Plan Sequences Synergy Capture", "Owners And Milestones For Each Workstream", "Retention Of Key People Identified In DD", "Quick Wins Versus Structural Change"]$x$::jsonb, $x$Diligence should not just price the deal - it should generate the integration roadmap. The risks and synergy opportunities surfaced in DD become the workstreams in the integration plan, each with an owner and a milestone. Day-1 is about continuity and control: making sure payroll runs, customers and employees see no disruption, systems and bank accounts work, the right people have authority, and any transitional services agreements are in place where functions are still shared with a seller in a carve-out. The first 100 days is where you sequence the value capture - standing up the new operating model, locking in the key people that DD flagged as retention risks, going after quick wins that fund the program, and then tackling the harder structural changes like systems consolidation. I would tie every synergy number back to the diligence that supports it, set realistic milestones, and be honest that revenue synergies take longer and carry more risk than cost ones, so the plan should not front-load credit for them.$x$),
(1856, NULL, 'primary', $x$Due Diligence$x$, $x$AI And Data DD$x$, 'advanced', 3, 'analyst', 'Global', $x$You are diligencing a tech-enabled target that markets itself as an AI company. Beyond the usual tech review, what would you specifically test about its AI and data to judge whether the moat and the model are real?$x$, $x$["Distinguish Real AI From Wrapper Branding", "Data Rights Ownership And Provenance", "Dependence On Third Party Foundation Models", "Model Performance And Customer Outcomes", "Privacy IP And Training Data Liability", "Cost To Serve And Margin At Scale", "Talent Retention And Key Engineer Risk"]$x$::jsonb, $x$First I want to know whether the AI is real or branding - is there proprietary modeling and a genuine data advantage, or is this a thin wrapper over a third-party foundation model that any competitor could replicate. That leads straight to data: who actually owns the training data, where did it come from, are the rights and provenance clean, and would customer or privacy restrictions limit how it can be used or retrained. I test dependence on external model providers, because if pricing or access from one vendor changes, the unit economics and the product can move overnight. I look at real model performance tied to customer outcomes and retention, not demo metrics, and I probe IP and liability around training data, since scraped or improperly licensed data is a growing legal exposure. With rates higher, buyers scrutinize cash conversion hard, so I check cost to serve - inference and compute can quietly crush gross margin at scale. Finally I assess key-engineer and talent retention, because in these businesses the moat often walks out the door.$x$);
